<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25185d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25185d">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25185d"> 185(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> went from god to / god till they cried / from me in me / O thou I</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Sufis]</font> wrote poems of a most extraordinary nature&mdash;divine love-songs like those <font color="green">[246]</font> of the worshippers of Krishna. They practised the ancient hypnotism, and believed that they attained to union with deity. They founded orders, with novices and initiates, teaching absolute obedience to the chief. In the tenth century A.D. Bayazid of Bistam was a Moslem pantheist, believing in self-annihilation (Fana), and apparently mad with ecstasy. <mark>&ldquo;I went,&rdquo; he said, &ldquo;from god to god till they cried from me in me &lsquo;O Thou I&rsquo;&rdquo;</mark>; &ldquo;I am God&rdquo;; &ldquo;I am Love, the throne, the tablet, the pen&rdquo;; &ldquo;I made my heart a mirror; for a year I gazed; I saw all created things dead; by God&apos;s aid I attained to God.&rdquo; <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 246-7</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14125f" href="c14all.htm#c14125f">VI.C.14:125(f)</a>, <a name="c14125g" href="c14all.htm#c14125g">VI.C.14:125(g)</a>, <a name="c14125g" href="c14all.htm#c14125g">VI.C.14:125(g)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
